        {
            "content_html": "<img src=\"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/6770?u=85e683e6edf44982a2d847e6bb28c63a53fbc43e&v=4\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" alt=\"\"/><br/><p dir=\"auto\">One of the benefits of using Webfinger is that it's possible, at least in theory, to use non-ascii characters for usernames. Unfortunately, there are not a lot of services that support them -- at least according to our document.</p>\n<p dir=\"auto\">For the top human languages, only 3 primarily use only non-ASCII characters (English, Malaysian, Indonesian), for a total of about 500 million people. That means about 90% of humans use languages with non-Latin, or accented, character sets.</p>\n<p dir=\"auto\">We have an opportunity to let people in the global majority use their names or words in their own language as usernames.</p>\n<p dir=\"auto\">This is a huge win for making software that focuses on real people.</p>\n<p dir=\"auto\">I propose we start:</p>\n<ul dir=\"auto\">\n<li>Working on proof-of-concept implementations that use non-ASCII characters in <code class=\"notranslate\">preferredUsername</code>, <code class=\"notranslate\">webfinger</code> and the Webfinger username (with percent hashes)</li>\n<li>Report issues on major ActivityPub implementations to start the process of supporting non-ASCII characters in usernames</li>\n<li>Track interoperability</li>\n</ul>",
            "url": "https://github.com/swicg/activitypub-webfinger/issues/29",
            "title": "Tracking support for non-ascii characters",
            "date_modified": "2025-10-07T19:54:51.000Z",
            "date_published": "2025-08-02T17:52:46.000Z",
            "author": {
                "name": "evanp",
                "url": "https://github.com/evanp"
            }
        },
        {
            "content_html": "<img src=\"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/in/1375152?v=4\" width=\"64\" height=\"64\" alt=\"\"/><br/><markdown-accessiblity-table><table role=\"table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th></th>\n<th>URL</th>\n<th>Author</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>News</td>\n<td><a href=\"https://shkspr.mobi/blog/2020/09/dont-trust-cloudflare-with-your-personal-data/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://shkspr.mobi/blog/2020/09/dont-trust-cloudflare-with-your-personal-data/</a></td>\n<td>shkspr.mobi</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Original</td>\n<td><a href=\"https://shkspr.mobi/blog/2020/09/dont-trust-cloudflare-with-your-personal-data/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://shkspr.mobi/blog/2020/09/dont-trust-cloudflare-with-your-personal-data/</a></td>\n<td>Terence Eden</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></markdown-accessiblity-table>\n<hr>\n<p dir=\"auto\">The author details their frustrating experience with Cloudflare, who continued to send marketing and service emails for over a year after the author cancelled their account and requested data deletion. Despite repeated requests and escalations to the CTO, the issue was not resolved, raising serious concerns about Cloudflare's respect for GDPR and their data management practices. The author concludes that Cloudflare cannot be trusted with personal data.</p>\n<hr>\n<p dir=\"auto\">筆者は、Cloudflareアカウントをキャンセルしデータ削除を要求した後も、1年以上にわたってマーケティングやサービスに関するメールが送られてき続けたという苛立たしい経験を詳述している。度重なる要求やCTOへのエスカレーションにもかかわらず問題は解決されず、CloudflareのGDPR遵守やデータ管理体制に深刻な懸念を投げかけている。筆者は、Cloudflareは個人データを預けるに値しないと結論づけている。</p>",
            "url": "https://github.com/xhiroga/news/issues/411",
            "title": "A User's Struggle: Cloudflare's GDPR Compliance Questioned After Repeated Unwanted Emails / CloudflareのGDPR遵守に疑問符：アカウント削除後も続く迷惑メール、あるユーザーの闘いの記録",
